\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Prompting Strategy and Extraction Workflow\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 We employed a 
\f0\b two-tier prompting strategy
\f1\b0  for structured extraction of breast imaging and pathology features from clinical reports.\
First, a 
\f0\b zero-shot, schema-constrained extraction prompt
\f1\b0  was used for primary feature extraction. This production prompt enforced strict non-inferential behavior, required explicit evidence for each extracted element, and returned standardized JSON outputs. The prompt was optimized to minimize fabrication by restricting outputs to information explicitly stated in the source document and assigning \'93Not reported\'94 or \'93Indeterminate\'94 when information was absent or ambiguous.\
Second, for audit and adjudication purposes, we used a 
\f0\b guideline-constrained chain-of-thought prompting approach
\f1\b0 . This prompt enumerated the allowable classification options for each feature (e.g., receptor status categories, imaging descriptors) and provided explicit guideline-based definitions to guide internal reasonin. Fin. The model was instructed to refer to these definitions when resolving uncertainty or ambiguity. Importantly, although the prompt induced stepwise internal reasoning, the model was not permitted to output its reasoning; only final structured classifications and supporting evidence spans were returned.\
This two-tier design mirrors clinical abstraction workflows, in which initial extraction is followed by guideline-informed adjudication when uncertainty arises. Separating production extraction from guideline-constrained reasoning reduced overfitting to guideline expectations while preserving high-fidelity classification for ambiguous cases.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 Fabrication Control and Missingness Handling\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Across both prompting stages, the model was prohibited from inferring unstated findings. Any element not explicitly documented in the source text was labeled as \'93Not reported,\'94 and conflicting statements were labeled as \'93Indeterminate\'94 with verbatim evidence excerpts. This approach ensured that apparent completeness did not arise from hallucinated content and allowed missingness patterns to be analyzed directly.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 Rationale for Chain-of-Thought Use Without Reasoning Disclosure\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The guideline-constrained prompt was classified as a chain-of-thought method because it required the model to reason over enumerated decision spaces and explicit definitions. However, intermediate reasoning was intentionally kept internal to avoid verbosity, reduce the risk of post-hoc rationalization, and maintain clinically usable outputs.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

